The appointment of Mojtaba Khamenei as Iran's Supreme Leader isn't just a succession — it's a signal. It tells us where the regime is headed: deeper entrenchment, tighter alignment with the IRGC, and a sharply diminished appetite for compromise. Understanding why requires looking at three dynamics that converged to produce this outcome.

## Who is Mojtaba Khamenei?

Khamenei Junior entered the Western public eye a few months ago when news of his wealth surfaced. But he has been playing a growing role in his father's court for over a decade, consistently mentioned as a possible heir. While usually not the top candidate, he lurked in the shadows, enjoyed the disappearance of other contenders — like President Ebrahim Ra'isi, who mysteriously died in a helicopter crash, with some calling it a deliberate act — and eventually secured the big prize. Probably not in the way he had hoped for it to happen.

We don't yet know what process took place at the Council of Experts, the 88-cleric body constitutionally tasked with selecting the Supreme Leader once the existing one dies. But we can make several presumptions, some relating to long-term dynamics in Iranian ruling-elite politics and some distinctly tied to the war during which Khamenei Senior was assassinated.

## 1. Mojtaba is an extremist — and will need to prove it

We don't have a full picture of his worldview because he rarely spoke publicly, but he has taken a tough stance on multiple domestic and external questions. He is therefore likely to be *tougher* than his father (who also wasn't exactly a moderate), especially with the need to prove himself worthy of the position.

This matters enormously for what comes next. A new leader consolidating power under wartime conditions, with a legitimacy deficit and something to prove, is not a leader who will seek de-escalation.

## 2. The IRGC alliance is now existential

Mojtaba's extremism connects directly to his dependency on the IRGC — the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps — both as a political necessity and as an ideological alliance. We may not know all the new commanders who have emerged after their predecessors were killed, but we know what they grew up with, and it is hard to assess whether they will lean to change that which will undermine their position.

This is a self-reinforcing dynamic: Mojtaba needs the IRGC to govern, and the IRGC needs a Supreme Leader who won't constrain them. The result is an axis that is structurally resistant to moderation.

## 3. The moderate line is finished

There's a wider point here. Other candidates, like Hasan Homeini (grandson of the first Supreme Leader), didn't stand a chance with their more moderate platform — precisely because of this alliance. The moderate line, which won popularity with the public in presidential elections, had gradually lost its weight within Khamenei Senior's inner circle. The mandate of presidents to change policies became weaker and weaker, while domestic repression and diplomatic and military extremism took the front.

This wasn't a sudden shift — it was a long erosion. Mojtaba's appointment simply makes it official.

## So what's next?

These three points frame the answer to the critical question. When the regime's very existence is perceived by the Mojtaba-IRGC axis as being threatened from both outside and inside Iran, steadfast refusal to capitulate is likely to be the response.

This puts Mojtaba on a trajectory very different from the one Delcy Rodriguez of Venezuela took upon the removal of her predecessor, Maduro. Where Maduro's circle ultimately calculated that accommodation was survivable, the Mojtaba-IRGC axis is more likely to calculate that accommodation is *itself* the threat. The ideology, the wartime context, and the consolidation logic all point in the same direction: double down.

## The legitimacy question

What will the Iranian public's response be? One of the main arguments against Mojtaba's succession has always been legitimacy. In a regime where the Supreme Leader is supposedly the most learned Ayatollah, Mojtaba is not even a relevant figure in clerical terms. The façade cracks further, and the people are likely to notice the slogans of the republic — which behaves like a monarchy — ring hollow, just like the one toppled by the 1979 revolution.

Does this bring the fall of the regime closer? That depends mainly on how tight the bonds within the regime remain: whether moderates who were in the past loyal interpret this as a breaking point, and whether the internal and external pressures connect into an explosive combination.
